This one I'm just standing in front of.

00:46:20.004 --> 00:46:26.282
TRAVIS: We're coming across a lot of these. If we
need to make a quick escape, it might be a

00:46:26.282 --> 00:46:27.201
problem.

00:46:27.201 --> 00:46:29.421
SAM: If we're going back out the way we came in?

00:46:29.421 --> 00:46:30.486
TRAVIS: In a hurry.

00:46:30.486 --> 00:46:32.237
TALIESIN: We'll just have to remember.

00:46:32.237 --> 00:46:33.647
TRAVIS: Oh yeah.

00:46:33.647 --> 00:46:35.635
MARISHA: Hopefully, we won't be in a
hurry.

00:46:35.635 --> 00:46:37.985
SAM: Well we'll just have Trinket run first.

00:46:38.069 --> 00:46:42.340
LIAM: I'm sure you've got something in that bag of
yours that we can plop in front of this. For now,

00:46:42.340 --> 00:46:43.644
let's just get past it.

00:46:43.644 --> 00:46:56.858
MATT: All right, so you each make your way around
this. When it comes to Trinket's side, I'll say

00:46:56.908 --> 00:47:00.874
for you because he'll probably need a little help
making his way across so go ahead and just make a

00:47:00.874 --> 00:47:05.472
dexterity check for Trinket with advantage, with
the aid from the party.

00:47:05.472 --> 00:47:09.581
LAURA: Okay, that's not good. Eight?

00:47:09.581 --> 00:47:12.121
MATT: Eight? Okay.

00:47:12.121 --> 00:47:12.988
LIAM: Plus anything?

00:47:12.988 --> 00:47:13.787
LAURA: Nope!

00:47:13.787 --> 00:47:14.690
MARISHA: That's for Trinket?

00:47:14.690 --> 00:47:15.433
LAURA: Yeah.

00:47:15.433 --> 00:47:17.125
MATT: Okay, so who's helping Trinket?

00:47:17.125 --> 00:47:21.110
LIAM: I am. We are, I assume.

00:47:21.110 --> 00:47:22.382
TRAVIS: I'll help Trinket.

00:47:22.382 --> 00:47:28.546
TALIESIN: I'll also say, if this was a gas trap, I
would probably throw my mask on before passing it,

00:47:28.546 --> 00:47:29.792
as well.

00:47:29.792 --> 00:47:31.086
TRAVIS: I'll help Trinket.

00:47:31.086 --> 00:47:33.276
MATT: Okay, so just you, Grog?

00:47:33.276 --> 00:47:34.530
TRAVIS: Just me.

00:47:34.530 --> 00:47:43.215
MATT: Okay, as everyone continues pushing forward,
you reach out, helping Trinket get along.

00:47:43.215 --> 00:47:49.416
Trinket's pushing up the side of the cavern, claws
scraping on the side of the wall. Foot slips,

00:47:49.416 --> 00:47:57.591
slams into the mound of dirt, at which point, the
mound depresses and then (explosion) bursts open

00:47:57.591 --> 00:48:03.362
into a 20 by 20-foot gas cloud.

00:48:03.362 --> 00:48:10.494
MARISHA: Can I cast Gust of Wind really quick and
push it back down the hallway?

00:48:10.494 --> 00:48:14.386
MATT: You can start doing that because it is a
lingering cloud effect. Regardless, I need you and

00:48:14.386 --> 00:48:16.734
Trinket to both make a constitution save.

00:48:16.734 --> 00:48:22.917
TRAVIS: Yes! 21! Nope, 20

00:48:22.917 --> 00:48:25.035
MATT: Laura, can you roll a constitution save for
Trinket?

00:48:25.035 --> 00:48:28.857
LAURA: (nervous laugh) Yeah--

00:48:28.938 --> 00:48:30.032
TRAVIS: 17!

00:48:30.032 --> 00:48:32.685
LAURA: Just regular?

00:48:32.685 --> 00:48:34.592
MATT: Just a regular constitution save.

00:48:34.592 --> 00:48:35.595
LAURA: Seven.

00:48:35.595 --> 00:48:43.904
MATT: Seven? Okay. You suffer six points of poison
damage, Trinket suffers 12 points of poison

00:48:43.904 --> 00:48:44.936
damage.

00:48:44.936 --> 00:48:49.610
SAM: Grog, you suffer no poison damage. We had our
meal.

00:48:49.610 --> 00:48:50.964
TRAVIS: Heroes' Feast!

00:48:50.964 --> 00:48:52.337
LAURA: And Trinket ate it, too!

00:48:52.337 --> 00:48:54.098
MARISHA: That's true!

00:48:54.098 --> 00:48:55.692
LAURA: We're immune to poison?

00:48:55.692 --> 00:48:57.664
MARISHA: We're immune to fear and poison.

00:48:57.664 --> 00:49:00.264
LAURA: (gasps) That's amazing!

00:49:00.264 --> 00:49:07.394
MATT: As the cloud begins to fill the area, you
breathe it in and there's that reactionary point

00:49:07.394 --> 00:49:12.428
of like, "Shit, get Trinket out of there!" and
then you realize the harshness of the toxin

00:49:12.428 --> 00:49:18.806
doesn't seem to be affecting your system. There is
some element of the "holy shit it's delicious"

00:49:18.806 --> 00:49:25.726
feast you guys had that is keeping the toxins at
bay from entering your system.

00:49:25.726 --> 00:49:28.523
TRAVIS: I spent the last few years building up an
immunity to iocane powder.

00:49:28.523 --> 00:49:30.256
(laughter)

00:49:30.256 --> 00:49:33.400
MARISHA: Also, doesn't your belt of Dwarvenkind
have something like that?

00:49:33.400 --> 00:49:34.264
TRAVIS: Nope.

00:49:34.264 --> 00:49:37.028
MARISHA: No? Okay, never mind.

00:49:37.028 --> 00:49:40.597
LAURA: He just grows a beard. You have advantage
on charisma?

00:49:40.597 --> 00:49:43.224
TRAVIS: I have resistance against poison damage.

00:49:43.224 --> 00:49:45.308
LAURA: You have advantage on persuasion checks.

00:49:45.388 --> 00:49:46.297
TRAVIS: I know.

00:49:46.297 --> 00:49:47.667
LAURA: That's awesome.

00:49:47.667 --> 00:49:49.953
MATT: You take half poison damage whenever you do
take poison damage.

00:49:49.953 --> 00:49:52.885
LAURA: Oh, where did Pike go?

00:49:52.885 --> 00:49:57.465
SAM: No Pike! The evil of this place is making it
hard to maintain her connection.

00:49:57.465 --> 00:49:59.488
MARISHA: I know it's hard. It's deep underground.

00:49:59.488 --> 00:50:01.003
LIAM: Oh!

00:50:01.003 --> 00:50:02.813
MARISHA: Hey!

00:50:02.813 --> 00:50:06.412
ASHLEY: This astral projection is very hard to
hold.

00:50:06.412 --> 00:50:08.197
(laughter)

00:50:08.197 --> 00:50:11.765
MATT: That's all right.

00:50:11.765 --> 00:50:13.764
TALIESIN: We live in an age of miracles and
wonders.

00:50:13.764 --> 00:50:16.754
MATT: So as you guys pass under this cloud, you--

00:50:16.754 --> 00:50:18.950
ASHLEY: The connection is just not very strong.

00:50:18.950 --> 00:50:25.647
MATT: That's all right, it's much better now.
Keyleth, you push the toxin cloud back and hit it

00:50:25.716 --> 00:50:30.061
off to the side, pushing it down the same tunnel
that the acid section was. It'll take you a while

00:50:30.061 --> 00:50:32.757
to get it back there, but you can just leave it
lingering in the tunnel if you'd like.

00:50:32.757 --> 00:50:34.642
MARISHA: No, it's fine. I'll just leave it. It's
fine.

00:50:34.642 --> 00:50:40.063
MATT: Okay. It seems to be pervasive for now. It
may eventually fade or sink into the earth, but

00:50:40.063 --> 00:50:48.905
it'll take a while for that to happen. But you
move past this trap. You continue forward and the

00:50:48.905 --> 00:50:57.643
descent grows steadily more and more steep at this
point. What was like a relative decline has now

00:50:57.643 --> 00:51:02.268
gotten to the point where some of you have to get up
against the wall as you step down, not to the

00:51:02.268 --> 00:51:06.338
point where it's slide-worthy or anything, but
enough where it gets a little precarious for those

00:51:06.422 --> 00:51:14.170
who don't have quite as much a grand hold on loose
earth. About five minutes of this, it evens out

00:51:14.170 --> 00:51:20.733
though, and as it does you come to a metallic
doorway.

00:51:20.733 --> 00:51:22.608
TRAVIS: Of course.

00:51:22.608 --> 00:51:24.245
LAURA: God damn doors.

00:51:24.245 --> 00:51:26.673
SAM: I got this.

00:51:26.673 --> 00:51:28.779
TRAVIS: Please just do it.

00:51:28.779 --> 00:51:30.511
LAURA: Inspect it for traps!

00:51:30.511 --> 00:51:31.744
TRAVIS: No, let him take it!

00:51:31.744 --> 00:51:36.166
LIAM: Why don't I look, and then Scanlan can
handle it? I'm just going to look, all right?

00:51:36.166 --> 00:51:39.271
Yeah, 23.

00:51:39.271 --> 00:51:44.683
MATT: Okay. The door does not appear to be
trapped, but it is locked.

00:51:44.683 --> 00:51:47.136
LIAM: Well.

00:51:47.136 --> 00:51:48.429
LAURA: Can you pick it?

00:51:48.429 --> 00:51:49.670
LIAM: Probably.

00:51:49.670 --> 00:51:51.036
TRAVIS: Metal door, right?

00:51:51.036 --> 00:51:52.046
MATT: Yeah.

00:51:52.046 --> 00:51:53.170
LIAM: Natural 20.

00:51:53.170 --> 00:52:00.468
MATT: All right. So, looking at the door, and the
closer you get as you bring some light source to

00:52:00.468 --> 00:52:09.985
it you can see the door itself is not an iron or a
slate metal, it's hammered bronze.

00:52:10.054 --> 00:52:14.988
The surface is semi-smooth but it does have
a bit of a warp to it from when the

00:52:15.061 --> 00:52:19.736
metal was originally plied and used to create this
doorway, so it has this hammered look across its

00:52:19.736 --> 00:52:26.254
entire surface, some small rivets in the side. You
do notice that there is no handle for it but on

00:52:26.254 --> 00:52:32.397
the other side of the door, there is something
that is latched over it, so using your dagger, you

00:52:32.397 --> 00:52:39.844
manage to lift it slightly and then shove forward
through the slight edge of the door frame to the

00:52:39.844 --> 00:52:44.999
door itself or means to force this off of its
latch and you hear the metallic arm bang against

00:52:44.999 --> 00:52:48.169
the other side of the door as it falls down, and
the door pushes open slightly.

00:52:48.169 --> 00:52:51.757
LIAM: I look back to the group and go, it won't
open, it won't--

00:52:51.757 --> 00:52:54.199
(laughter)

00:52:54.199 --> 00:53:00.374
LIAM: I don't push it that far, only like four or
five inches just to peer through.

00:53:00.374 --> 00:53:07.855
MATT: Okay. That same acrid smell that has
permeated into the hallway continues into this

00:53:07.855 --> 00:53:14.370
room, it's a little colder; the temperature in
this room is because, as you notice, looking in,

00:53:14.370 --> 00:53:20.800
what little bit of distance you can see in this
pitch black vicinity, the entire room is made of

00:53:20.800 --> 00:53:23.368
this type of hammered bronze.

00:53:23.368 --> 00:53:31.435
TRAVIS: Before we go in, are there any bits of
whitestone on the ground, like stuff in chunks or

00:53:31.435 --> 00:53:33.366
small pieces or is it pretty clean-ish?

00:53:33.366 --> 00:53:40.283
MATT: As you travel through here you see chunks
here and there, some of them appear to be, yeah,

00:53:40.283 --> 00:53:43.910
nothing bigger than what you can fit in your palm.
Any of the larger pieces seem to have made their

00:53:43.910 --> 00:53:50.400
way all the way back to the undercroft where you
guys had the ghost battle. At this point, you've

00:53:50.400 --> 00:53:53.509
just seen bits and pieces that may have fallen out
of whatever carts were brought through and you do

00:53:53.509 --> 00:53:56.541
see grooves in the ground where like large wheeled
carts were pushed back and forth up and down this

00:53:56.541 --> 00:53:59.658
tunnel to carry materials to and from.

00:53:59.658 --> 00:54:05.109
LIAM: I pull the door a little bit shut behind me
and turn to the group and say, this is a room

00:54:05.109 --> 00:54:12.538
made entirely of metal that presumably did not
exist five years ago. I think this is probably

00:54:12.538 --> 00:54:20.584
bad. Sister, dear, would you help me look? Just
from the door, please? Just look.

00:54:20.584 --> 00:54:22.671
TRAVIS: Scanlan, just shoot a lightning bolt in
there.

00:54:22.671 --> 00:54:27.017
LIAM: No, in a moment. Please. And perception
check the room from here.

00:54:27.017 --> 00:54:28.228
MATT: Go for it.

00:54:28.228 --> 00:54:32.124
LIAM: 29.

00:54:32.124 --> 00:54:42.495
LAURA: Oh, that's good, that's better than mine,
but not much. 23?

00:54:42.495 --> 00:54:43.904
TRAVIS: Question mark?

00:54:43.904 --> 00:54:49.511
MATT: Okay. Both glancing in what little bit of
space you have to poke through, you can see the

00:54:49.511 --> 00:55:00.288
room itself, it's about 80 feet across and about
50 feet wide. From the doorway, it's a slight ramp

00:55:00.288 --> 00:55:06.645
that leads down into an open floor area, also the
bronze metal, and then across the way another ramp

00:55:06.645 --> 00:55:13.519
that rises up to meet a small upper platform area.
and there appears to be a door

00:55:13.519 --> 00:55:14.771
on the opposite side.

00:55:14.771 --> 00:55:22.110
LAURA: Can I do an arcana check, or something, to
see if it's magic?

00:55:22.110 --> 00:55:27.912
MATT: If you'd like to. You'd probably have to get
a little closer into the room to check it out

00:55:27.912 --> 00:55:33.346
because you guys are at the outskirts of it.
You're just able to see a little bit of the edge

00:55:33.346 --> 00:55:34.787
of your visual distance.

00:55:34.787 --> 00:55:36.237
MARISHA: How big is the door?

00:55:36.237 --> 00:55:39.450
MATT: Looking at the door, if you open it up? It's
about two inches thick.

00:55:39.450 --> 00:55:49.965
LIAM: Pike, Keyleth, will you come up here? We're
a little out of our depths here. This seems suspect

00:55:50.020 --> 00:55:51.692
to me. I'd like you to both have a look.

00:55:51.692 --> 00:55:53.005
MARISHA: Yeah, something's going on here.

00:55:53.005 --> 00:55:54.496
ASHLEY: Yeah.

00:55:54.496 --> 00:55:58.528
MARISHA: So Pike and I are going up.

00:55:58.528 --> 00:55:59.815
ASHLEY: Yeah.

00:55:59.815 --> 00:56:02.524
LAURA: Go. Tell us what's up.

00:56:02.524 --> 00:56:09.126
MATT: Have you guys all moved up to the door, at
least? Or are you all still back in the corridor?

00:56:09.126 --> 00:56:10.843
SAM and TALIESIN: I'm moving up to the door.

00:56:10.843 --> 00:56:12.284
LAURA: I'm stepping a little back.

00:56:12.284 --> 00:56:16.734
MATT: Okay. Cassandra does say, "This is as far as
I've gone down here."

00:56:16.734 --> 00:56:19.223
LAURA: Do you know what's on the other side?

00:56:19.223 --> 00:56:25.317
MATT: "I assume the project. The last time I came
here, I was following the Briarwoods at a

00:56:25.370 --> 00:56:31.114
"distance. They went in there with a handful of
guards, and when I made it to this door, it was

00:56:31.114 --> 00:56:35.839
"empty on the inside. I assume they traveled
through that far door, but I have not actually

00:56:35.839 --> 00:56:39.932
"been here myself. It was at that point that I was
discovered and dragged back to the castle."

00:56:39.932 --> 00:56:41.930
TALIESIN: Did you make it to the acid pits?

00:56:41.930 --> 00:56:47.980
MATT: "Back that way? I saw them, from a distance.
I did not want to get too close. They're just

00:56:47.980 --> 00:56:59.311
"larger, stone troughs that these chemicals have
been refined in, and for whatever purpose they've

00:56:59.311 --> 00:57:05.338
"required them, have been kept there. Dr. Ripley,
actually, was in charge of a lot of that

00:57:05.338 --> 00:57:07.502
"development and creation."

00:57:07.502 --> 00:57:14.903
MARISHA: Percy and Cassandra, does this material
mean anything to you? The bronze? Does it keep any

00:57:14.903 --> 00:57:20.054
type of energy out? Why build a room out of
bronze?

00:57:20.054 --> 00:57:23.767
LIAM: That's a question for you, as well,
Percival.

00:57:23.767 --> 00:57:27.375
TALIESIN: I don't know. I would like to get a
better look. Are there markings on the walls? Is

00:57:27.375 --> 00:57:28.745
there any scripting?

00:57:28.745 --> 00:57:31.357
MATT: Make a perception check.

00:57:31.357 --> 00:57:38.484
TALIESIN: Get that out of the way. Nine?

00:57:38.484 --> 00:57:46.186
MATT: Okay. As you step into the room and look
along the walls at the top of the ramp that leads

00:57:46.186 --> 00:57:57.918
downward, there's no discerning features that you
